Discovering Bestsellers with R

Cleaning, analysing and visualizing data

By Alexandre Kocev


Blue Island is a shipping company operating all over the world and selling a large variety of products.
The purpose of this analysis is to determine the best sellers in terms of revenue for each geographical areas. The final results will be presented to the Operations and Marketing vice presidents allowing them to adapt their supply and marketing strategies for each geographical area. The final goal is to increase sales by selecting the best products for each region as well as to limit shipping and storage costs.
The data is made of the last four years of sales records. Each annual record is contained into one csv file.


The original data was created by Jonathan Major and collected from here. It was then reorganized by myself for the purpose of this case study.


STEP 1 : Set up the workspace and read the data

Import required packages.

library(tidyverse) #wrangle data
library(lubridate) #convert date attribute
library(dplyr) #manipulate data
library(ggplot2) #visualize data
library(scales) #calculate values as percent and currency
library(gridExtra) #arrange graphs
library(knitr) #draw tables on rmarkdown

Upload four csv files as Blue Island sales records.

sales_2017 <- read.csv('2017_sales_record.csv')
sales_2018 <- read.csv('2018_sales_record.csv')
sales_2019 <- read.csv('2019_sales_record.csv')
sales_2020 <- read.csv('2020_sales_record.csv')

total_sales <- total_sales %>%

total_sales[total_sales == '' | total_sales == ' '] <- NA

total_sales <- total_sales %>%

We identify several negative inputs. Stakeholders confirm a minus sign was accidentally added and those inputs should be positive.

# convert values to absolute values
total_sales$units_sold <- abs(total_sales$units_sold)
total_sales$unit_price <- abs(total_sales$unit_price)
total_sales$unit_cost <- abs(total_sales$unit_cost)

We see one outlier at the amount of sold units. The stakeholder confirms that three zeros were accidentally added. We update to the right amount.

# divide the max outlier by 1000 to remove three zeros
total_sales['units_sold'][total_sales['units_sold'] == max(total_sales$units_sold)] <- max(total_sales$units_sold)/1000

Furthermore, we update names to be shorter.

total_sales['region'][total_sales['region'] == 'Australia and Oceania'] <- 'Oceania'
total_sales['region'][total_sales['region'] == 'Central America and the Caribbean'] <- 'Central America'
total_sales['region'][total_sales['region'] == 'Middle East and North Africa'] <- 'Middle East'


(5) Convert date columns from string to date format

# convert string to date format as month/day/year
total_sales$order_date <- mdy(total_sales$order_date)
total_sales$ship_date <- mdy(total_sales$ship_date)
# sort dataframe based on descending order dates
total_sales <- total_sales %>% 
  arrange(desc(order_date))


(6) Add calculated fields

We add new columns such as total revenue, cost and profit. This will help us for further analysis.

# calculate Total Revenue, Total Cost and Total Profit for each observation
total_sales <- total_sales %>% 
  mutate(total_revenue = units_sold*unit_price) %>% 
  mutate(total_cost = units_sold*unit_cost) %>% 
  mutate(total_profit = total_revenue - total_cost)


(7) Add extra variables if further analysis is needed. This is optional.

Dates are too granular to analyse trends. We aggregate dates of orders into a new column.

# aggregate dates under quarters
total_sales <- total_sales %>% 
  mutate(order_qtr = quarter(order_date, with_year = T))

We add a new calculated field as “preparation_time” for showing the duration between receiving and shipping orders.

# subtract Ship Date to Order Date to get the duration of order preparation
total_sales$preparation_time <- difftime(total_sales$ship_date, total_sales$order_date, units = c('days'))

(2) Confirm the time frame of our data collection

message("Data was collected from ", min(total_sales$order_date), " to ", max(total_sales$order_date))
## Data was collected from 2017-01-01 to 2020-07-28

We calculate a new variable as the time difference in year between first and last observations. It will be used later in the analysis to find average annual revenue and profit.

year_diff <- time_length(difftime(max(total_sales$order_date), min(total_sales$order_date)), unit="years")


(3) Look at an overview of sales

We show regions and their average annual revenue.

# calculate average annual Revenue, grouped by Region 
revenue_by_region <- total_sales %>% 
  select(region, total_revenue) %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  summarize(avg_annual_revenue = sum(total_revenue)/year_diff) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg_annual_revenue))

(5) Look at the correlation between revenue and profit

High revenue doesn’t necessarily mean high profits. Let’s look at the correlation between those two variables.

# visualize correlation between Profit and Revenue and colored by Item Type
ggplot(total_sales) +
  aes(x=total_revenue, y=total_profit, color=item_type) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title='Revenue vs Profit and by Product category', x='Revenue ($)', y='Profit ($)') +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank())


We see a positive correlation between revenue and profit. However, we see that certain product categories allow higher profits than others.


(6) Analyse profit per region and product category

Let’s analyse our product categories in terms of profit using profit ratio.

# calculate average annual Profit and Profit Ratio, grouped by Region and Item Type 
profit_ratio_region_item_type <- total_sales %>% 
  select(region, item_type, total_revenue, total_profit) %>%
  group_by(region, item_type) %>% 
  summarize(avg_annual_revenue = sum(total_revenue/year_diff), avg_annual_profit = sum(total_profit/year_diff)) %>% 
  mutate(avg_annual_revenue = round(avg_annual_revenue, digits =0), avg_annual_profit = round(avg_annual_profit, digits = 0), profit_ratio = round(avg_annual_profit/avg_annual_revenue*100, digits = 1)) %>% 
  arrange(region, desc(profit_ratio))
kable(head(profit_ratio_region_item_type), caption = 'We only show the first 6 rows', col.names = c('Region', 'Category', 'Average annual revenue', 'Average annual profit', 'Profit Ratio  (%)'))

Conclusion

As a final summary, we print out a table showing best sellers per region, revenue (showing as dollar), and including profit ratio (showing as percent).

# create a new table, calculate average annual Revenue, average annual Profit and Profit Ratio, grouped by Region and Item Type
summary_sales_2017_2020 <- total_sales %>% 
  select(region, item_type, total_revenue, total_profit) %>% 
  group_by(region, item_type) %>% 
  summarize(avg_annual_revenue = sum(total_revenue), avg_annual_profit = sum(total_profit)) %>% 
  mutate(profit_ratio = round(avg_annual_profit/avg_annual_revenue, digits=2)) %>% 
  arrange(region, desc(avg_annual_revenue))

We convert numerical values to currency or percent for better report comprehensiveness.

# define the dollar format
dollar_format(prefix='$', suffix='', largest_with_cents=1e+05, big.mark=',', negative_parens=FALSE)

# convert variables to dollar format
summary_sales_2017_2020$avg_annual_revenue <- dollar(summary_sales_2017_2020$avg_annual_revenue)
summary_sales_2017_2020$avg_annual_profit <- dollar(summary_sales_2017_2020$avg_annual_profit)

# define percent format
percent_format(accuracy=0.1, scale=100, prefix='', suffix='%', big.mark='', decimal.mark='.', trim=FALSE)

# convert variables to percent format
summary_sales_2017_2020$profit_ratio <- percent(summary_sales_2017_2020$profit_ratio)
